 in the 13th century. Etymologically speaking, the form with a fourth <i>-l-</i> is an error, not found as an original Welsh name, but this is now much the most common spelling in the US."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]},{"name":"ferch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferg","meanings":["1  ‘Sharp blade’.","2  ‘Wind’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice ferch Llywelyn was born about 1559, in Cadoxton, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom as the daughter of Llywelyn ap William. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Fleming."},"et":{"about 1559–":"umbes 1559–Surnud","1559–Female":"1559–Surnud","1455–Male":"1455–Surnud","1546–Male":"1546–Surnud","1485–Male":"1485–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1529–Male":"1529–Surnud","1546":"1546","1455":"1455","about 1559":"umbes 1559","1485":"1485","1529":"1529","1559":"1559","of Glyn-nedd,Cadoxton,Glamorganshire,Wales":"Cadoxton, Glamor